{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565145"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:23:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17213"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17213"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.09,0.1,0.52,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9903"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90031"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1102"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"7108"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-week history of worsening headache. She is 24 weeks pregnant with her first child and smokes 15 cigarettes per day. She has no significant medical history, takes prenatal supplements, and is otherwise on no medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. She has right-sided ptosis and diplopia on right lateral gaze. During the examination, she experiences a generalised tonic-clonic seizure lasting two minutes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idiopathic intracranial hypertension","Subarachnoid haemorrhage","Intracerebral haemorrhage","Cerebral venous thrombosis","Ischaemic stroke"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of cerebral venous thrombosis. The combination of pregnancy (a hypercoagulable state) and smoking significantly increases the risk. The gradual onset of headache with cranial nerve palsies and seizures is characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral venous thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with headache and features of raised intracranial pressure. Involvement of the cavernous sinus can cause multiple cranial nerve palsies (III, IV, V and VI). The pathophysiology of these cranial nerve palsies relates to the anatomical location of these nerves within or adjacent to the cavernous sinus. The oculomotor (III), trochlear (IV), and abducens (VI) nerves travel through the cavernous sinus, while the ophthalmic and maxillary divisions of the trigeminal nerve (V) run in the lateral wall. When thrombosis occurs, venous congestion leads to compression of these nerves, resulting in ophthalmoplegia (diplopia), ptosis (drooping eyelid), and sensory changes in the face. The right-sided ptosis and diplopia on right lateral gaze in this patient are consistent with involvement of the right cavernous sinus. Seizures are present in 30-40% of cases and result from cortical irritation due to venous congestion, ischemia, or hemorrhagic transformation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic intracranial hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in pregnancy but typically affects overweight women and causes papilloedema with headache. While it can occasionally cause cranial nerve palsies, these are usually limited to the abducens nerve (CN VI) resulting in lateral gaze palsy due to increased intracranial pressure. The combination of ptosis (CN III) and diplopia seen in this patient would be unusual for IIH. Additionally, seizures are not a typical feature of IIH.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubarachnoid haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset, thunderclap headache. The gradual onset makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracerebral haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with focal neurological deficits and reduced consciousness. The pattern of multiple cranial nerve involvement would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIschaemic stroke\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with sudden onset focal neurological deficits. The gradual onset headache and multiple cranial nerve involvement would be atypical.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pregnancy is an acquired risk factor for cerebral venous sinus thrombosis due to its hypercoagulable state.","Headache with multiple cranial nerve palsies and seizures is characteristic of cerebral venous thrombosis.","Cavernous sinus thrombosis specifically causes ophthalmoplegia and ptosis due to compression of cranial nerves III, IV, and VI."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Kim J, Martinez C, Sirotkin I. Cerebral Venous Thrombosis. Fed Pract. 2017 Jul;34(7):33-37. PMID: 30766287; PMCID: PMC6370440."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90031"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17213"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90031"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-01T09:48:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T09:51:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9903"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https: